				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Canite wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&nbsp; LDA ballx<br />&nbsp; CLC<br />&nbsp; ADC #$08 ; does this mean I'm adding 8 pixels? <br />&nbsp; CMP paddle1x<br />&nbsp; BCC Collision1Done<br /></div></div><br />If the ball is moving to the right and is supposed to hit the left side of the paddle, then this should work. The carry will be clear if the ball is at the left of the paddle. Of course you still have to check the Y coordinates, since the paddle probably doesn't extend all the way from the top of the screen until the bottom, right?<br /><br />The most common way of checking for collisions is actually to check for the 4 conditions that make it impossible for a collision to happen. Something like this (this is called bounding box collision detection):<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">if BallLeft &gt; PaddleRight goto NoCollision<br />if BallRight &lt; PaddleLeft goto NoCollision<br />if BallTop &gt; PaddleBottom goto NoCollision<br />if BallBottom &lt; PaddleTop goto NoCollision<br /><br />;the ball is touching the paddle<br /><br />NoCollision:</div>
<br />If any of those conditions is true, a collision is impossible. A collision only happens if all of those fail. If you do it like this, it doesn't matter in what direction the objects are moving, if they are overlapping you'll know.
<br />
<br />To calculate the values for left, right, top and bottom you'll use the coordinates and dimensions of the sprites, like we talked before:
<br />
<br />Left: X;
<br />Right: X + width;
<br />Top: Y;
<br />Bottom: Y + width;
<br />
<br />If you are using sprite coordinates directly (which you shouldn't, but it's forgivable since you are just starting), remember to subtract 1 from the Y coordinates.</div>

